      "\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.3 -/\n\ndef parts₃ {α : Type} : List α → List (Partition α) :=\n  let step (x : α) : List (Partition α) → List (Partition α)\n   | [[]] => [[[x]]]\n   | ps => ps.map (cons x) ++ ps.map (glue x)\n  List.foldr step [[]]\n\n-- #eval parts₃ [1,2,3]\n\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.4 -/\n\nsection\nopen List (filter all head!)\n\ndef ok (xs : List Nat) : Bool :=  xs.all (· > 0)\n\ndef okextendl (x : Nat) : Partition Nat → List (Partition Nat) :=\n filter (ok ∘ head!) ∘ extendl x\n\nvariable (h : ∀ x ps, filter (flip all ok) (concatMap (extendl x) ps) =\n              concatMap (okextendl x) (filter (flip all ok) ps))\n\nexample\n  : List.filter (flip List.all ok) ∘ parts₁ = List.foldr (concatMap ∘ okextendl) [[]] := by\n  funext xs\n  unfold parts₁\n  simp [Function.comp]\n  induction xs with\n  | nil =>\n    simp [List.foldr, flip]\n  | cons a as ih =>\n    have h1 := h a\n    sorry\n```\n\nThe problem is that we have a hypothesis `h1` which is a general lemma, and we need to apply it in the inductive step. The structure of the goal involves `List.foldr` while the hypothesis `h1` is about `concatMap`.\n\nLet's think more carefully. The goal is:\n`filter (flip all ok) (List.foldr (fun x => fun y => insert x y ++ filter (fun y' => y' ≠ x) y) [[]] (a :: as)) = List.foldr (fun x => fun y => insert x y ++ filter (fun y' => y' ≠ x) y) [[]] (a :: as)`\n\nBut `List.foldr (fun x => fun y => insert x y ++ filter (fun y' => y' ≠ x) y) [[]] (a :: as)` is equal to `(fun y => insert a y ++ filter (fun y' => y' ≠ a) y) (List.foldr (fun x => fun y => insert x y ++ filter (fun y' => y' ≠ x) y) [[]] as)`\n\nSo, the left side of the equality is `filter (flip all ok) ((fun y => insert a y ++ filter (fun y' => y' ≠ a) y) (List.foldr (fun x => fun y => insert x y ++ filter (fun y' => y' ≠ x) y) [[]] as))`\n\nAnd the right side is `List.foldr (fun x => fun y => insert x y ++ filter (fun y' => y' ≠ x) y) [[]] (a :: as)`\n\nThis is getting very complicated. Let's think about 